<button class="accordion">What skills do you need to be a trainer?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Every trainer needs to have several skills as well as training development tools to be practical. These include:</p>
<p></p><li>Essential skills for trainers</li>
<p></p><li>Advanced research skills</li>
<p></p><li>Strong communication skills</li>
<p></p><li>Flexible organisation skills</li>
<p></p><li>Enthusiasm for lifelong learning.</li><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the role of a health trainer?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Health trainers help their clients to assess their lifestyles and wellbeing, set goals for improving their health, agree on action-plans, and provide practical support and information that will help people to change their behaviour. This could include promoting the benefits, taking regular exercise and eating healthily.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What does a health and wellbeing advisor do?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The wellbeing advisor supports and motivates smokers to stop smoking, 
supports and drives individuals to lose weight, supports and motivates people to reduce their alcohol intake, or supports and motivates individuals with low-level emotional health issues or other complex behavioural needs.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What entry qualifications and training do you need?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The certificate for health trainers covers things like:</p>
<p></p><li>Helping people make healthier food choices</li>
<p></p><li>Assisting people to diet, exercise and stop smoking</li>
<p></p><li>Addressing people's behaviour towards health</li>
<p></p><li>Motivating people to change.</li><p></p>
<p>You will study for this nationally recognised certificate as a trainee health trainer because you have to be in full-time employment to do the training. Once you've got your certificate, you can work as a full health trainer.</p>
</div>
